comment.body:
@Muja: Still a database of torrents technically. :P

Ignoring my joke, some people really don't want to host certain kinds of content, especially if they don't want to waste space for whatever reason. A distributed torrent site should be able to accommodate something like that. And for those worrying about censorship, I'm pretty sure there will be plenty of people willing to seed the NSFW hubs :)

The other benefit to having the torrents in hubs is that it emphasizes the fact that anybody could create their own torrent site front-end and then tap into the same hubs. This also solves the issues that some sites like ZeroTorrent have had where a user would run out of their allowed space on the site preventing them from making more uploads. With a hub system the user could simply switch to a different hub and continue uploading without having to hope that the creator of whatever site will up the user space allotment.

@12hlearn: Zeromux can allow file download and there's a video player you can setup now that can stream the video directly in browser. It's all done in Javascript on the client side so no plugins are needed. Only major issues right now are incompatibility with UIPassword and Zeronet proxies that use HTTPS in Chrome.
[Here's a Test Stream I setup](http://127.0.0.1:43110/1FyYahC8sKVYfsPQXEzuRjXNDQeb6Y2xno/__example-player__.html)
[And here's a higher quality video example from the Dev](http://127.0.0.1:43110/1CiDoBP8RiWziqiBGEd8tQMy66A6fmnw2V/big/?type=video/mp4&codecs=avc1.640028,mp4a.40.2&json=files/yrc_op_mp4/file.json&poster=files/yrc_op_mp4/poster.png)

@Jmsebastian: If you already have them formatted for HTML it might be easier to just adapt your existing HTML so that it plays nice with Zeronet(remove external sources, make paths relative, etc) and then straight publishing that to Zeronet instead of importing them into Zeroblog. Just make sure to add the `"optional": "(.*.jpg|.*.png|.*.gif)",` to your `content.json` file to make the images and other large files an optional download instead of something that has to be downloaded up front.

I did a rough job of this myself when I wanted to archive a TED talk webpage. Here's the result: http://127.0.0.1:43110/14MQWAD4DNSWx52pidtux4oQXz4gTn4B5f/

Though depending on how your stuff is structured it could be more work than it's worth. At that point it'd probably be easier to just manually import into Zeroblog like discussed before.
